The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                               Business Briefs
                              
	 Calcutta, March 23: Titagarh Wagons Ltd (TWL) is planning to merge two group companies with itself. The TWL board will meet on March 28 to consider the merger of its wholly owned subsidiary Titagarh Biotech and group firm Titagarh Steels Ltd (TSL). The promoters of TWL own a 49.25 per cent stake in the company and around 35 per cent in TSL.                             
	 Calcutta, March 23: Srei Infrastructure Finance has tied up with Netherlands-based financial institution FMO for a $100-million external commercial loan. This is over and above the $47-million exposure that FMO already has in the city-based firm.                             
	 New Delhi, March 23: The government today issued bonds worth Rs 10,000 crore to oil marketing PSUs to compensate them for selling some petroleum products below the cost price. The bonds will carry an 8 per cent coupon rate and will mature in 2026, the government said.                            
	 London, March 23: Mahindra amp; Mahindra (M amp;M) may buy LDV, which is struggling to keep afloat, according to The Times. Mahindra amp; Mahindra is one of the two companies vying to buy LDV, the Birmingham-based van maker owned by Oleg Deripaska, it said.                            
	 Mumbai, March 23: Punjab National Bank (PNB) said credit growth in the bank could dip to 20 per cent in the next fiscal because of the economic slowdown.                            
	 New Delhi, March 23: Reliance Industries Ltd has raised the marketing margin on the natural gas it will sell from its eastern offshore KG-D6 field by 25 per cent to $0.15 per million metric British thermal unit from $0.12 per mmBtu.                             
	 Dubai, March 23: Aabar Investments, Abu Dhabis state investment fund, has decided to invest 1.95 billion euros ($2.65 billion) in Daimler. This will make it the single biggest shareholder in the group.                                                                                                                           
